● Putting on the institutional-PM hat. The philosophy is internally coherent
  and far more honest than 95% of retail-facing material — but you asked for
  the holes, so here they are.

## What's actually strong

#1 (alpha = articulable mispricing), #4 (humility about day trading), #6
  (vol surface), #9 (scope discipline), #11 (passive-income myth), #12
  (Keynes). These are all things institutions agree with internally but
  won't say in marketing. Keep them.

## The soft spots

**#1 — "Most of the time" is too generous to you.** Even when the market
  *is* wrong, it's usually wrong in a way you can't monetize: the wrongness
  is the compensation for a risk you haven't measured. Most retail
  "mispricings" are known risk premia (illiquidity, distress, fat-tail) that
  the holder is paid to bear. Your variant view has to be specifically
  *about that risk*, not about price. Worth tightening.

**#2 — You've been right in principle for ~10 years and the passive trade
  keeps working.** What's your actual trigger? "When the tailwinds reverse"
  is the same answer perma-bears have given since 2014. By #12's own logic,
  being early to this view is expensive. And even if passive breaks, what
  replaces it for retail? Active funds underperform net-of-fees by Sharpe's
  arithmetic identity — that's a math constraint, not a market one. Without
  a successor strategy, the principle is a warning, not a position.

**#3 — Lumping productive equity into "all consensus" is sloppy.** Gold has
  zero cash flow. Fiat pays nominal interest. Equities and real estate
  generate *real* cash flow. The "all faith-based" frame is true at the
  metaphysical level but flattens an operationally important distinction.
  Recommend a sentence acknowledging that productive cash-flow assets are a
  different category from non-productive stores of value, even if both
  ultimately rest on someone honoring the claim.

**#5 — Each of your "real alphas" has been heavily arbed.**
  Liquidity-watching was Druckenmiller's edge in the '90s; now every macro
  fund tracks the Fed balance sheet on Bloomberg. Front-running passive
  flows is real but quants with millisecond latency know reconstitution
  dates better than you do. Sector rotation in textbooks is easy; in live
  trading it's mostly momentum dressed up. Long-term trends pay, but they
  require eating 5-15 years of underperformance (uranium thesis ran ~15
  years before paying). The bigger meta-issue: **if all your durable alphas
  are structural/macro, you're a macro investor teaching what looks like an
  equity course.** Worth being honest about that to students.

**#6 — Overstated for retail.** Vol surface is a genuinely informative
  second source, but the marginal alpha from incorporating it on a $100K
  portfolio is small relative to the cognitive overhead. The stronger, more
  defensible version of your point: *TA in isolation is unreliable; any
  independent second source improves it.* Vol is one good source, not the
  only valid one. The current wording will read as "you must master dealer
  gamma" to a beginner, which is wrong.

**#7 — You're declining a documented factor premium.** Small-cap value is
  one of the most empirically robust premia in academic finance
  (Fama-French, AQR's replications). Your "$1B floor" is a *trade-off* —
  you're saying the messiness isn't worth the premium, *for you*. That's
  defensible. But the principle should say "this costs me a known premium
  and I accept that," not present sub-$1B as definitionally gambling. Some
  of it is gambling; some of it is the small-cap value premium you're
  choosing not to harvest.

**#8 — Two regimes is a useful heuristic but an incomplete framework.** Real
  regime taxonomies have at least four axes (vol-on/off, risk-on/off,
  dispersion, correlation). Reducing to mom/MR misses range-bound chop,
  which is "neither," and where most regime-rule strategies bleed.

**#13 — Phase 3 is brutal in practice.** Shorting late-bubble explorers gets
  squeezed (GME, ARKK shorts). Borrow is expensive or recalled exactly when
  you need it. Historical beta ratios *blow out at extremes* — the regime in
  which you want to bet on convergence is precisely the regime where your
  historical sizing stops applying. The principle is right; the execution
  risk is much higher than the current text suggests. Recommend a "this is
  the hardest tranche of the playbook and most retail attempting it will be
  stopped out" caveat.

## What's missing

These would strengthen SOUL.md if you want them in:

1. **Position sizing as first-order discipline.** It's mentioned only inside
  #12. For someone who has survived decades, sizing is probably more central
  to your survival than any alpha source. The pros' real edge over retail
  isn't security selection — it's risk management.
2. **After-tax returns.** Conspicuously absent. Tax is the single biggest
  "fee" most retail pays. A philosophy that ignores tax systematically
  overestimates the value of high-turnover strategies (your own sector
  rotation and momentum playbooks).
3. **Currency / home bias.** Especially live for the HK/TW/CN audience. A
  USD-equity portfolio is a *choice*, not a default.
4. **Behavioral edge over institutions.** You allude to it in CLAUDE.md
  ("retail can hold cash, no benchmark pressure") but it isn't a SOUL
  principle. It should be — it's one of the few *durable* retail edges and
  the opposite of #5's structural edges (which institutions access better
  than you).
5. **Convexity / tail-hedge thinking** (Taleb / Spitznagel). For retail with
  limited capital and #8's regime-switch risk, asymmetric payoff structures
  are arguably the most important framework you haven't named.
6. **Explicit "circle of competence" / what you don't know.** Implied in #4
  and #7 but never named. A SOUL of only convictions feels asymmetric —
  Buffett-style explicit humility about blind spots earns more credibility
  than any of the convictions on their own.

## One bigger meta-observation

The philosophy reads as a *discretionary macro investor's* worldview applied
  to equities. That's coherent — it's a real and respected school. But the
  course markets itself as built on the CFA curriculum, which is
  fundamentally a *bottom-up security analysis* tradition. There's a quiet
  tension: you teach DCF and ratios because the canon requires it, but your
  actual alpha sources have nothing to do with bottom-up valuation. Worth
  either (a) naming the tension explicitly to students, or (b) adding a SOUL
  principle that says "the canon teaches bottom-up; my edge is top-down;
  here's how I reconcile them in my own portfolio."

That's the honest read. Take or leave any of it — most of these are
  sharpening, not refutation.

