❯ why there are two cash line?  what are the difference?

● The two gray lines show the **same cash pile** measured in two different
  units:

**1. Cash (nominal)** — dashed line
The literal dollar amount sitting in Person B's drawer at the end of each
  year. Just the running sum of deposits: $10K, $20K, $30K… $550K at the end
  of the full window. This is what a bank statement would show.

**2. Cash (real, start-year $)** — dotted "ghost" line
The same cash pile, but expressed in the **purchasing power of the window's
  start year**. If Person B had $20K nominal in 1972 and inflation was 3.2%
  in 1972, the real value in 1971 dollars is $20K ÷ 1.032 ≈ $19,380. Over
  the full 55-year window, $550K of nominal cash becomes only ~$66K in 1971
  purchasing power, because cumulative inflation was 728%.

The dotted line is the visual punchline: even though the dashed line keeps
  climbing as B keeps depositing more dollars, inflation is silently eroding
  what those dollars can actually buy. The gap between dashed and dotted
  *is* the inflation tax.

**Why I included both:** the dashed line tells the literal "what's in the
  drawer" story; the dotted line tells the "what does it buy" story.
  Together they make the inflation-eats-cash point visible — that's the
  whole reason "B uses cash with CPI adjusted" was in your spec for
  principle #3 of SOUL.md.

**If it's cluttering the chart**, two reasonable simplifications:
- **Drop the dotted line entirely** — let the stats panel and the markdown
  carry the inflation point in text instead.
- **Replace the dashed line with the dotted one** — only show real
  (purchasing-power) cash, which is more honest for the comparison since A
  and C also implicitly carry inflation effects.

Want me to make either of those changes?

