❯ when the initial captial is not zero.  why the first year doesn't start at
  the same value?

● Good catch. The reason: in the math, **the first year's return already
  applies to B and C by the end of year 1**, while A (cash) has no return —
  so the very first plotted point already shows divergence. With
  initial=$500K, year 1 = $510K (A) / $532K (B) / $583K (B in 1971's S&P
  year). They diverge before you see them.

The fix is to prepend a **start-of-window anchor point** at `(startYear − 1,
  initialCapital)` so all three lines begin from exactly the same dot before
  any year's return is applied.

