**1. Anchor point added when initial capital > 0.**
The interactive's `compute()` now prepends a `(startYear − 1, initial)`
  anchor for all three series whenever `initial > 0`. The chart now visibly
  starts all three lines from the **same dot at the initial capital**, then
  they fan out year by year as deposits land and returns accrue. With
  `initial = 0` (the default), no anchor is added — the lines start at year
  1 the same way they always did, which avoids any log-scale
  undefined-at-zero weirdness.

I also fixed a follow-on bug the anchor would've caused: the `Deposited`
  stat was computed from `yrs.length`, which would now over-count by one
  annual deposit (the anchor isn't a real year of investing). Switched to
  `endIdx − startIdx + 1` so the deposited total stays mathematically
  correct: `initialCapital + annualDeposit × actualYears`.

**Math behind the gap (so the explanation in this thread holds up):** with
  `initial = $500K` starting in 1971, end-of-year-1 values are A=$510K
  (cash, no return), B=$510K × (1+0.0434) = $532K (T-bills earned 4.34%),
  C=$510K × (1+0.1431) = $583K (S&P returned 14.31%). Now you see them
  anchored together at $500K and fanning out from there.

