❯ does katex support github markdown style $$...$$$?

● Short answer: **yes, KaTeX supports `$$...$$` natively** — it's literally a
  default delimiter in the `auto-render` extension. I deliberately disabled
  it on this site, and there's a real reason that's worth being explicit
  about.

**Why I left it off:**

Every lesson is full of monetary references — `$10,000`, `$2.71`, `$1.73M`,
  etc. KaTeX's `auto-render` is dumb: it scans the DOM for delimiter pairs
  and tries to render whatever it finds between them as math. With `$...$`
  enabled, *every* sentence like "Person A ends up with $510K, Person B with
  $532K" gets the chunk `510K, Person B with ` parsed as math and rendered
  as garbled symbols. There's no way to opt out per-mention without escaping
  every dollar sign in the lesson.

GitHub's parser is much smarter — it requires the `$` to NOT be adjacent to
  digits/word chars to be treated as a math delimiter, so `$5,000` is safe.
  KaTeX's auto-render does not have that guard. (There's a `pre-process`
  hook you can write yourself, but it's fragile.)

**Three options if you want the GitHub style:**

| Option | What changes | Risk |
|---|---|---|
| **A. Add `$$...$$` only** | Display math via `$$ FV = PV(1+r)^n $$`.
  Inline math still uses `\(...\)`. | Low — `$$` rarely appears organically
  in prose. Still risky in tables that show two prices like `$$5 vs $10$$`.
  |
| **B. Add `$$...$$` AND `$...$`** | Full GitHub style. | High — every
  monetary reference breaks unless escaped to `\$`. Would require re-editing
  every lesson. |
| **C. Implement GitHub-style guards** | Custom pre-processor in `build.py`
  that only treats `$` as math when not adjacent to digits/letters. | Medium
  — extra ~20 lines of regex; matches GitHub behavior exactly. |

**My recommendation:** keep `\(...\)` and `\[...\]` as the primary
  delimiters (what you have now), and **add Option A** so you can also write
  `$$...$$` for display math when convenient. That gives you
  GitHub-compatible display math without the dollar-sign minefield. If you
  ever want to author lessons in GitHub's web editor and have the math
  preview work there, that's the lowest-risk way.

Want me to enable Option A? It's a one-line change in `build.py`'s KaTeX
  config — add `{left: '$$', right: '$$', display: true}` to the delimiters
  array.

