❯ how does the static chart and interactive chart handles different languages?

● Honest answer: **right now, neither localizes.** Both show in English
  regardless of which language the host page is in. This is a real gap and
  worth being explicit about.

## Current state

**Static PNG charts** (`course/image/*.png`)
- Generated by matplotlib in the Python scripts. Every title, axis label,
  legend entry, and annotation is hardcoded as an English string in `.py`
  source.
- One PNG file. The build's `copy_lesson_assets` copies it to `docs/image/`
  once.
- All four language pages (`week01.html`, plus the HK/TW/CN versions inside
  the same `<div class="lang-content">` containers) reference the same
  `image/week01_three_portfolios.png`. So the Chinese reader sees the chart
  titled "*Three Portfolios, Same $10,000/year Deposit, 1971–2025*" with
  English legend even when the prose around it is in Traditional Chinese.

**Interactive HTML charts** (`course/interactive/*.html`)
- Standalone HTMLs with their own embedded JS/CSS/strings. Every string —
  slider labels ("Initial value", "Annual rate", "Years"), stat-card names
  ("After 25 yrs"), captions, hover templates — is hardcoded English in the
  source.
- The iframe `<src>` doesn't carry locale info. The iframe also doesn't read
  its parent's `<html lang="...">` because cross-frame access is not
  currently wired up.
- So same iframe, same English content, on all four locale variants of the
  page.

The only piece of the lesson UI that *does* localize is the **markdown prose
  around the charts** (translated by `scripts/translate-batch.py` into
  `course_hk/`, `course_tw/`, `course_cn/`) and the chart's `alt` attribute
  (since alt is plain text inside the markdown). The chart visual itself
  stays English.

The site **is** correctly per-language elsewhere — the chatbot
  (`web_assets/chatbot.js`) has a full `I18N` table covering EN/HK/TW/CN for
  every label, and switches based on `currentLocale()` reading the page's
  `data-theme`-adjacent locale state. The chatbot is the model to copy.

## What it would take to fix

**Option A — full localization (more work, properly correct):**

For **static PNGs**:
1. Refactor each Python generator to accept a `--lang` arg, with an `I18N`
  dict at the top covering the four locales (titles, axis labels, legend,
  annotations).
2. Generate four PNGs: `week01_three_portfolios_en.png`, `_hk.png`,
  `_tw.png`, `_cn.png`.
3. Update `build.py`'s `swap_interactive_components` (and the prose `<img>`
  rendering) to pick the right PNG per the locale of the surrounding `<div
  class="lang-content">`.

For **interactive HTMLs**:
1. Add an `I18N` object at the top of each interactive HTML covering the
  four locales (mirror the chatbot pattern).
2. The iframe reads its locale from a URL parameter (e.g.,
  `interactive/X.html?lang=hk`) — `build.py` would emit four iframes per
  chart, one per `lang-content` block.
3. OR a postMessage protocol: parent sends `{type: 'set-lang', lang: 'hk'}`
  whenever the user toggles language, iframe re-renders with the new
  strings. This is more elegant but requires wiring on both sides.
4. Plotly's tooltip format strings, axis tick formats, and date/number
  formats also need locale-appropriate forms.

**Option B — light-touch localization (cheaper):**

1. Strip text from the static PNGs entirely — make them figure-only with no
  titles or legends, and write the title/legend/caption in the surrounding
  markdown (which IS translated). This is how research papers handle figures
  in multilingual journals.
2. For interactives, do the I18N table approach — it's mostly mechanical
  work, ~100 strings × 4 locales.

**Option C — defer (current state):**

Accept that charts are English-only, with a note in the lesson saying so.
  Pragmatic if the audience reading the Chinese versions is comfortable with
  English chart labels (most finance professionals worldwide are).

## Recommendation

Charts that are **content-heavy in text** (titles explain the story, legend
  identifies the people, axis labels quote currencies and units) should be
  properly localized — Option A. The three-portfolios and inflation charts
  both fall into this bucket: a Chinese reader getting "**Person C — S&P 500
  (dividends reinvested)**" in English on an otherwise-translated page is
  jarring, and the title "*Where you put your savings matters more than how
  much you save*" carries pedagogical weight that should land in their
  native language.

Charts that are **mostly visual** (a flowchart, a simple time-series with
  self-evident axes) might be fine in English under Option C.

If you want, I can take Option A on the two existing chart pairs as a first
  concrete pass — extract the strings into `I18N` tables in both the Python
